# Cursor AI Rules for layered-zero-trust project

## Documentation Organization

### RHTAS Documentation
- All RHTAS (Red Hat Trusted Artifact Signer) documentation should be placed in `/home/minzhang/ZTVP/RHTAS/`
- This includes:
  - Architecture documents
  - Integration guides
  - Configuration examples
  - Troubleshooting guides
  - API references
  - Design documents
- Use descriptive filenames in UPPERCASE (e.g., `SPIFFE-INTEGRATION.md`, `DEPLOYMENT-GUIDE.md`)
- Keep chart-specific technical configuration in `charts/rhtas-operator/` but move high-level documentation to `/home/minzhang/ZTVP/RHTAS/`

### RHTPA Documentation
- All RHTPA (Red Hat Trusted Profile Analyzer) documentation should be placed in `/home/minzhang/ZTVP/RHTPA-DOC/`
- This includes:
  - Architecture documents
  - SPIFFE/SPIRE integration guides
  - Vault integration documentation
  - Configuration examples
  - Troubleshooting guides
  - API references
  - Design documents
- Use descriptive filenames in UPPERCASE (e.g., `SPIFFE-VAULT-INTEGRATION.md`, `DEPLOYMENT-GUIDE.md`)
- Keep chart-specific technical configuration in `charts/rhtpa-operator/` but move high-level documentation to `/home/minzhang/ZTVP/RHTPA-DOC/`

### Documentation Standards
- Use Markdown format for all documentation
- Include table of contents for documents over 50 lines
- Add code examples with proper syntax highlighting
- Include architecture diagrams using ASCII art or Mermaid
- Document all configuration options with default values
- Provide troubleshooting sections with common issues

### Code Organization
- Helm charts in `charts/` subdirectories
- Values files at repository root following pattern: `values-*.yaml`
- Scripts in `common/scripts/` or `scripts/`
- Tests in `tests/` subdirectory

### Branch-Specific Rules
#### layer1-rhtas-test branch
- Focus on RHTAS integration and testing
- All RHTAS-related documentation goes to `/home/minzhang/ZTVP/RHTAS/`
- RHTAS Helm chart in `charts/rhtas-operator/`
- Keep configuration changes tracked with clear commit messages

#### rhtpa-spiffe-integration branch
- Focus on RHTPA integration with SPIFFE/SPIRE and Vault
- All RHTPA-related documentation goes to `/home/minzhang/ZTVP/RHTPA-DOC/`
- RHTPA Helm chart in `charts/rhtpa-operator/`
- Document SPIFFE JWT authentication flow and Vault integration
- Keep configuration changes tracked with clear commit messages

## Coding Standards

### Helm Templates
- Use semantic versioning for charts
- Follow Helm best practices for template structure
- Include _helpers.tpl for reusable template functions
- Add comments for complex template logic
- Use values.yaml for all configurable parameters

### YAML Files
- Use 2-space indentation
- Quote string values that could be interpreted as other types
- Use `---` to separate multiple YAML documents in a single file
- Add inline comments for non-obvious configuration

### Shell Scripts
- Use `#!/bin/bash` shebang
- Set `set -e` for error handling
- Add function documentation
- Use meaningful variable names
- Include usage examples in comments

## Security

### Secrets Management
- Never commit actual secrets to git
- Use values-secret.yaml.template for secret structure
- Actual values-secret.yaml is gitignored
- Store secrets in Vault
- Document required secrets in README or documentation

### Access Control
- Document required RBAC permissions
- Use service accounts for automation
- Follow principle of least privilege
- Document any elevated permissions needed

## Git Workflow

### Commit Messages
- Use conventional commits format
- Prefix with type: feat, fix, docs, chore, refactor, test
- Include issue/ticket numbers when applicable
- Keep first line under 72 characters
- Add detailed description for complex changes
- **ALWAYS use `-s` flag when committing** to add Signed-off-by line
  - Example: `git commit -s -m "feat: add new feature"`

### Branch Naming
- Use descriptive names: layer1-rhtas-test, feature/spiffe-integration
- Keep branches focused on specific features or fixes
- Document branch purpose in first commit or PR description

## Code Style

### No Emojis or Decorative Symbols
- **NEVER use emojis** in code (Python, Go, Shell, YAML, etc.)
- **NEVER use decorative symbols** like ✅ ❌ ⚠️ 🎯 🚀 etc. in code
- **NEVER use emojis** in documentation files (Markdown, etc.)
- Use plain text only: "SUCCESS" not "✅", "ERROR" not "❌"
- Keep code and documentation professional and text-only
- Exception: Standard symbols like -, *, #, etc. for formatting are acceptable

